caption: Rice & beans were good but the chicken was a bit flavorless. Recently tried this pIace because we ordered delivery for a team lunch. The food came on time. I was going to go with my normal Cuban sammie but then I thought, you know what? The pork was a little bit dry, but the green sauce fixed everything. I pretty much doused the entire container with a mix of the green sauce, white sauce, and orange sauce (no idea what each of them were). But it was like a double-edged sword. While it tasted great, I found myself needed to glug water afterwards, just to balance out my sodium levels. So just be careful!  I think next time, I'll go back to basics and get my sammie.

Found this while visiting, just happen to look it up via Yelp & I must say this had a wide variety of excellent Cuban dishes. Being Cuban myself I'm quite critical of Cuban restaurants. It's very busy for the Wall Street lunch crowd. If you're looking for a quiet lunch place, move on, this will not be a place for you. Lots of good conversations going on & very little people on their phones or computers. They're too busy enjoying the Cuban atmosphere & when the food arrives you're too busy enjoying it. They have a To Go section, one for just sandwiches that are placed on 'la plancha' (or panni press), the other for all the fresh meals that have been made for the day. They had 'arroz con pollo', 'chuletas', 'ropa vieja', rice, congri (rice infused/cooked with black beans)'plantain-maduros', & 'plantain-tostones'. So much more. Well worth the wait for seating or if you're coming in for 'to go'. Cheers to a 'authentic' Cuban place near Wall Street. Quite a surprise.
